            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00E8</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00E8.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Bicategories of natural models">Bicategories of natural models</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>There are several possible bicategories of <fr:link href="jms-00E4.xml" title="Algebraic description of natural models" addr="jms-00E4" type="local">natural models</fr:link>, corresponding to different allowances of laxness. All of these are, in fact, (strict) 2-categories — but we see this as a meta-level statement as it concerns definitional equality.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>By “the” bicategory of natural models, we shall refer to the one in which 1-cells are <fr:link href="jms-00E5.xml" title="Homomorphisms of natural models" addr="jms-00E5" type="local"><fr:em>strong</fr:em> homomorphisms</fr:link>. This bicategory is precisely the one described by <fr:link href="uemura-2023-mscs.xml" title="A general framework for the semantics of type theory" addr="uemura-2023-mscs" type="local">Uemura</fr:link>; in his <fr:link href="uemura-2021-thesis.xml" title="Abstract and Concrete Type Theories" addr="uemura-2021-thesis" type="local">doctoral thesis</fr:link>, the same author considered the (2,1)-subcategory with invertible 2-cells. The latter bicategory benefits from the <fr:link href="lurie-htt.xml" title="Higher topos theory" addr="lurie-htt" type="local">Lurie’s theory</fr:link> of <fr:em>presentable (∞,1)-categories</fr:em>; <fr:link href="uemura-2023-mscs.xml" title="A general framework for the semantics of type theory" addr="uemura-2023-mscs" type="local">Uemura</fr:link> has also claimed an appropriate form of presentability for the full bicategory with non-invertible 2-cells, but neither precise definitions nor proofs of this condition have been published.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
